[normal]WIDER ECONOMIC BENEFITS[bold]The KMPG claim[bold]KPMG, acting for HS2 Ltd, claim that the 
[normal]“Y” 
[normal]network, connecting 
[normal]London to Birmingham and Manchester and Birmingham to Nottingham, Sheffield and Leeds will generate £15bn per year in Wider Economic Benefits, the so called WEBs.
[normal] This extraordinary value is circa 15 times higher than the annual value implied by the 
[normal]£
[normal]13.3b
[normal]n discounted value claimed in the October 2013 Economic Case
[normal].
[normal]The WEBS[bold]All these WEBs
[normal], or nearly all, should be assigned to the generated or new trips since 
[normal]the other trips, and most of their associated WEBs, would arise in the absence of the scheme.
[normal]Source documentation suggests that the proposal is forecast to generate 
[normal]circa 
[normal]98,800 new trips per day.
[normal] 
[normal]Dividing the £15bn by the 9
[normal]8,8
[normal]00
[normal] 
[normal]and by the 300 effective days in the year provides £5
[normal]0
[normal]0 per trip, or £1,
[normal]0
[normal]00 for a round trip.  Multiplying the £5
[normal]0
[normal]0 
[normal]by
[normal] the 1,460 million trips carried by Network Rail in 2011/12
[normal] generates circa £
[normal]73
[normal]0
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n, a sum equal to half the nation’s GDP; clearly an impossibility, implying that the £15bn is wildly optimistic.
[normal]  
[normal]Alternatively the WEBs could be assigned to the gener
[normal]ated business and commuter trips alone.  
[normal]Sources
[normal] suggest these are to 
[normal]number circa 3
[normal]7
[normal],000 per day.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Dividing the £15bn by 3
[normal]7
[normal],000 and the 300 days in the year yields £1,
[normal]350
[normal], or £2,
[normal]70
[normal]0 for a round trip.  Multiplying the £1,
[normal]35
[normal]0 by the nation’s business plus 
[normal]commuting trips provides an absurd £1
[normal]4
[normal],
[normal]3
[normal]00 billion,
[normal] some ten times the nation’s actual GDP, illustrating again how ludicrous it is that anyone should ever believe that the proposal could generate WEBs worth £15bn per year.
[normal]Note particularly 
[normal]that (a) these
[normal] extraordinary WEBs are in excess of what would have arisen had the new passengers stayed in their offices or at home or gone elsewhere (b) that the new passengers are supposedly generated by reductions in journey times of 30 to 60 minutes
[normal] (c) pre-existing trips on the West Coast Main line should have WEBs substantially above, perhaps double, those of the new and marginal trips
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]That leaves HS2 Ltd to either (a) explain why a High Speed Rail trip, generated merely because a journey has be
[normal]en shortened somewhat, should provide vastly more benefits than any other journey on the rail network ever could – a task made doubly difficult because
[normal], as above, 
[normal]the benefits from a generated, or marginal, trip should be lower
[normal] 
[normal]than 
[normal](perhaps half) 
[normal]those as
[normal]sociated with a pre-existing trip or (b) to throw the analysis into the waste paper basket.
