[normal]A [bold]fundamental flaw.[bold]The analysis depends on the so 
[normal]called ‘Willingness to Pay Calculus’ 
[normal]developed 
[normal]by Professor Sugden of the University of Ea
[normal]st Anglia.  
[normal]That 
[normal]‘
[normal]calculus
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]enables the incremental fares
[normal], namely the 
[normal]HS2 fares minus those lost to HS2 by the rest of the ra
[normal]i
[normal]lway
[normal], 
[normal]to be subtracted from costs and for the difference to be 
[normal]compared with the benefits.  
[normal]The problem is that the theory reduce
[normal]s to the absurd when it is realised that changing the eco
[normal]nomic 
[normal]boundary of the scheme (a matter that can be done at the stroke of a pen) 
[normal]would
[normal] change
[normal] the incremental fares.  
[normal]E.g. if we a
[normal]ssume the rest of the railway is proper
[normal]l
[normal]y privatised 
[normal]then 
[normal]the increm
[normal]en
[normal]tal fairs rise to the full HS2 fares.  
[normal]Alternatively w
[normal]iden the boundary to capture losses suffered by the airlines and the increm
[normal]en
[normal]ta
[normal]l
[normal] fares are reduced
[normal].
[normal]T
[normal]he correct place to draw 
[normal]the 
[normal]boundary is round the nation as a whole, not the Gove
[normal]rnment as pretended
[normal] in this analysis
[normal].  When th
[normal]e bou
[normal]ndary is 
[normal]so widened 
[normal]the incremental fares fall to zero since every pound spent on the railway is a pound lost elsewhere.
[normal]Striking out the
[normal]se
[normal] fares would of course destroy the economic case for this scheme and for all railway
[normal] 
[normal]projects
[normal].
